div.p:
"The Cleaveland property, real and personal, to your nephew, Mr. George Cleave;
                     the Free Hill estate and personalty to Miss Annie Bell; the railway and other
                     certificates of stock to Mr. Allan Gartrell?"

"My friend Jack don't mean to let the grass grow under his feet," he muttered;
                     "he has come to visit the fair chatelaine of this castle, and I think he shows
                     his taste!"

"Spoken like a man! and there is an adage that as good fish swim in the sea as
                     were ever caught out of it. You have missed your mark this time, George;
                     feather your shaft and shoot in some other direction."

Mr. Allan Gartrell perused this note with an expression of unmistakable terror.
                     Having read it slowly through once, he went back and read it through again;
                     studying it, as it were, sentence by sentence and word by word.

The figure of the maiden of old times was not unlike my little friend's to-day;
                     but the former one was much less gaily clad; her face was covered with a green
                     veil, and she was older—about seventeen.
